canonical_rel_desc: Indicates that an organism or taxonomic group has a specific stage type as part of its life cycle (e.g., egg, larva, pupa, adult), without implying a current temporal state of an individual.
Indicates that one life stage occurs before another life stage in the ordered life cycle of an organism.
Indicates that a female organism deposits its eggs on a specific substrate or host.

Indicates that the subject trait, structure, or behavior confers protection to a target (typically the organism or its offspring) by reducing harm or risk posed by the object (e.g., predators, environmental hazards).
Indicates that the subject process or activity is a contributing causal factor to the occurrence, maintenance, or magnitude of the object outcome or state.
A biological or physical process that directly acts on or alters a material entity as its target or substrate.
Denotes that a process causally leads to a specific outcome state, structure, or life stage.
Indicates that the subject is a more specific subtype, kind, or form within the broader category represented by the object.
Subject is a type of mimicry strategy that visually resembles the object in appearance or form, typically for camouflage or concealment.
Indicates that the subject entity includes the object entity as a physical or conceptual component or substructure.
Indicates that a specific life stage belongs to and is part of the life cycle of a given organism.
Indicates that a process or transformation takes place during a specific temporal phase or life stage.
A biological process causes structural or morphological change, including dissolution or reorganization, in anatomical structures of an organism.
Indicates that an anatomical structure or life stage gradually changes and becomes another anatomical structure or life stage over the course of development.
Indicates that the subject is situated at, on, or within the spatial region or physical substrate denoted by the object.
Indicates that a material or structure is converted into another material or structure, emphasizing physical or morphological transformation.
Indicates that one material or anatomical substrate serves as the developmental source or precursor from which another tissue or anatomical structure forms.
Indicates that a biological process culminates in or brings about a particular life stage of an organism.
Indicates that an organism or individual is currently in a specific life stage within its life cycle.
Indicates that an entity currently possesses or is in a particular physical or experiential state.
Links a specific state description to the underlying entity or part whose state it describes.
A biological entity (organism, anatomical structure, or life stage) that undergoes or participates in a specific biological process.
Indicates that a process or action causes a change from one state to another in the target entity.
Subject functionally enables or facilitates the occurrence or success of the object process/state, without implying strict determinism.
Indicates that an agent participates in or performs a specific process, activity, or behavior.
Indicates that a particular life stage includes or is characterized by a specific event or milestone.
Subject organism consumes the object as a food resource.
Subject anatomical structure is used as an instrument by the organism to feed on a food resource such as nectar.
Indicates that the subject entity is generated or produced by the object entity.
Indicates that an animal visits a plant structure (e.g., flowers), typically for feeding or other resource acquisition.
Indicates that an agent moves or carries biological material (e.g., pollen) from one location or organism to another.
Indicates that the subject entity generates or produces the object entity as an output or result.
Indicates that the subject serves as a food resource for the predator group represented by the object within a trophic interaction.
Indicates that the subject organism hunts, kills, and consumes the object organism as a food source (predation).
Indicates that an organism exhibits a specific ecological or functional role within an ecosystem.
Indicates that a life stage or organism is defined or typified by a particular behavior.
Indicates that an organism or life stage displays or engages in a specific behavior.
Links a biological life stage or organism to its characteristic lifespan or longevity.
Indicates that the value or characteristics of the subject are determined or constrained by the type or identity of the object.
Indicates that the subject entity is a component, aspect, or subset of the object entity, which represents a larger whole or system.
Indicates that studying or considering an entity helps reveal, explain, or improve understanding of another concept or process.
Indicates that an entity manifestly displays or expresses a particular state (e.g., aesthetic, behavioral, or experiential) under certain conditions.

Links a person, group, or audience to a psychological or sociocultural attribute it possesses (e.g., imagination, curiosity, fears, values, interests) that is relevant to the interpretation or transmission of urban legends.
Indicates that the subject, typically a group or community, consists of or includes the members represented by the object.
A document or essay examines, evaluates, or analyzes a specific topic, phenomenon, or question as part of its thematic scope.
Indicates that an academic or scholarly field includes a given subject as one of its research topics.
Indicates that an informational or cultural item circulates, is shared, or is transmitted within a given population or community context.
Indicates that the origins or beginnings of a phenomenon can be traced to a particular historical period or time span.
Indicates that a technology or system is employed to achieve a particular purpose or function.
Indicates that the subject enables, accelerates, or otherwise facilitates the dissemination or spread of the object (such as information, stories, or legends).
The subject exerts a shaping influence on how the object develops or changes over time.
Indicates that the subject enables, accelerates, or otherwise facilitates the spread of the object (such as information, stories, or legends).
Indicates the geographic extent or coverage area over which a phenomenon, process, or dissemination (such as the spread of urban legends) occurs.
An experiencer (person or group) undergoes or perceives a stimulus, event, or information.
Indicates that a narrative, document, or discourse segment has a particular topic, entity, or concept as its primary subject matter.
Indicates that the subject object is physically attached or fastened to the object entity in space.
Indicates that the subject and object refer to the same underlying physical object or token, possibly inferred rather than explicitly stated.
Indicates that the subject is a causal factor that leads to the occurrence or persistence of the object outcome or state, potentially under specified conditions or with uncertainty qualifiers.
A stimulus, condition, or abstract state (e.g., fear, threat) is mentally or emotionally experienced or perceived by an agent.
Indicates that the subject is a central recurring theme or motif within the narrative or narrative category represented by the object.
Indicates that two narrative elements or concepts are set in opposition or conceptual contrast to highlight their differences.
The subject is a specific example or member of the broader category represented by the object.
The subject affects the audience's belief or questioning regarding the existence or reality of the object.
The subject narrative or tale symbolically represents or mirrors the fears, anxieties, or concerns present in a society.
Indicates that two entities are linked through narrative, emotional, or conceptual association within a thematic or story context, without asserting direct causality.
Indicates that an agent intentionally selects another party as a victim or focus for harmful or exploitative actions.
Indicates that the subject uses the object specifically as bait to attract or lure a target.
Indicates that the subject functions as an enticing or attractive element that draws the attention, approach, or presence of the object, often enabling a subsequent harmful or instrumental action.
Indicates that two entities are linked through narrative, emotional, or conceptual association within a thematic or story context, without asserting direct causality.
Indicates that the subject issues a warning or cautionary message directed toward an audience represented by the object.
Indicates that a narrative or communicative artifact serves to alert an audience to specific risks, harms, or dangers.
The subject narrative portrays, includes, or represents the object as part of its narrative content (e.g., characters, threats, cursed items, or backstories).
Community or group circulates or communicates stories or narratives among its members.
Subject safeguards or provides protective benefit to the object (actual or intended protection), often against implicit or explicit threats.
Subject seeks or attempts to obtain protection against or from the object, which is construed as a source of potential harm or threat.
Indicates that an entity is exposed or vulnerable to potential harm or danger from another entity, whether the threat is real or perceived.
A story or narrative attains exposure to, or becomes accessible by, an audience.
Indicates that the subject attains awareness or recognition of the object.

Indicates that the subject phenomenon, process, or issue takes place within, or is embedded in, the broader contextual setting denoted by the object (e.g., societal, organizational, cultural, or procedural context).
Indicates a non-causal, conceptual association between two ideas or domains.
Indicates that the subject affects, shapes, or constrains how the truth or credibility of the object is judged or interpreted.
Indicates that the subject serves as factual or evidential support for the credibility or authenticity of the object claim or narrative.
Indicates that the subject gives rise to or generates the existence or proliferation of the object.
Indicates that a conceptual or categorical boundary separates the subject from the object, distinguishing them as different domains or categories.
Indicates that the conceptual boundary represented by the subject becomes indistinct or unclear within the narrative or situational context represented by the object.
Indicates that the subject stands in a correspondence relation to the object, typically aligning or matching it in meaning or truth-value, without strict identity of reference.
The subject (e.g., listeners) cognitively contemplates or ponders the truth or implications of the object narrative content.
The subject (a story form or folklore domain) captures the attention or interest of the audience.
Indicates that the subject is collectively associated with, or attributed to, the object (e.g., fears belonging to a particular society), without implying agentive control.
Indicates that the subject helps maintain or uphold the ongoing existence, intensity, or vitality of the object over time.
Indicates that the subject is a specific topic, aspect, or component that falls within the broader thematic or disciplinary domain represented by the object.
The subject is a broader set or category of ethical dilemmas in AI development that includes the object as a specific ethical issue or example.
Indicates that a system operates on or analyzes a data asset as part of its data processing activities.
Indicates that the use or presence of the subject creates a possibility or risk of the object outcome, without implying deterministic causation.
Indicates that the subject is a potential actor that may commit or engage in the specified abusive or harmful act, without asserting that it necessarily occurs.
Indicates that an actor or institution deploys or makes use of a technology or system.
Indicates that the subject AI system has been fitted or learned from the dataset represented by the object during a training process.
The subject is a specific problematic condition or state that the object can be in.
Indicates that the subject situation or condition can lead to or result in the object outcome as a potential consequence.
Connects an act or pattern of discrimination to the protected attribute (e.g., race, gender) that forms the basis or target of that discrimination.
Indicates that the subject is used within, or embedded in, a process, context, or larger system represented by the object.
Indicates that the subject (e.g., AI systems or their design and bias-handling choices) causally influences ethical outcomes such as fairness and equity in decision-making contexts.
Indicates that a process, policy, or framework is designed or expected to pursue a particular normative objective or outcome.
Indicates that the subject concept or system depends on the existence or establishment of the object as a necessary condition (often normative or constitutive).
Indicates that the subject is considered a possible bearer of accountability or responsibility for outcomes associated with an AI system, without asserting that accountability is actually assigned.

Indicates that the subject (such as a guideline, explanation, or governance mechanism) is designed to foster or ensure proper accountability in the context of AI development, deployment, or operation.
Indicates that a normative or regulatory instrument (e.g., guidelines, regulations, standards) governs, constrains, or is intended to cover the specified systems, entities, or activities.
Indicates that an ethical issue, dilemma, or concept is about or related to a particular system, domain, or context.
Subject causally reduces or hinders the uptake (acceptance or adoption) of the object.
The subject is a specific ethical issue or concern that is part of, or discussed within, the broader set or category of ethical dilemmas in AI development (the object).
Indicates that the subject impact or consideration functions as a contextual factor that must be weighed within the given ethical dilemma or decision context.
Indicates that the subject holds, owns, or has control over the object (which can be a tangible asset, power, or an abstract attribute such as fears or anxieties).
Indicates that a problem, risk, or dilemma is addressed, reduced, or managed through the application of a given principle, method, or mechanism.
Indicates that a principle, policy, or system gives higher normative importance to a particular value or outcome when guiding decisions or behavior.
Indicates that the subject has an effect on the state or well-being of the object, typically in a societal or stakeholder context.
Indicates that the subject (a mechanism, guideline, or practice) is used as a means to work towards achieving the object outcome or potential.
Indicates that the subject causally reduces the likelihood, severity, or impact of the specified harms, without necessarily eliminating them.
